{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SrabfjQ4v1k9RaFzGsp2db","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *\n2\t * Copyright by The HDF Group.                                               *\n3\t * All rights reserved.                                                      *\n4\t *                                                                           *\n5\t * This file is part of HDF5.  The full HDF5 copyright notice, including     *\n6\t * terms governing use, modification, and redistribution, is contained in    *\n7\t * the LICENSE file, which can be found at the root of the source code       *\n8\t * distribution tree, or in https://www.hdfgroup.org/licenses.               *\n9\t * If you do not have access to either file, you may request a copy from     *\n10\t * help@hdfgroup.org.                                                        *\n11\t * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * */\n12\t\n13\t#include \"H5LTprivate.h\"\n14\t\n15\t/* For Lex and Yacc */\n16\t#define COL       3\n17\t#define LIMIT     512\n18\t#define INCREMENT 1024\n19\t#define TMP_LEN   256\n20\t#define MAX(a, b) (((a) > (b)) ? (a) : (b))\n21\tsize_t input_len;\n22\tchar  *myinput;\n23\tsize_t indent = 0;\n24\t\n25\t/* File Image operations\n26\t\n27\t   A file image is a representation of an HDF5 file in a memory\n28\t   buffer. In order to perform operations on an image in a similar way\n29\t   to a  file, the application buffer is copied to a FAPL buffer, which\n30\t   in turn is copied to a VFD buffer. Buffer copying can decrease\n31\t   performance, especially when using large file images. A solution to\n32\t   this issue is to simulate the copying of the application buffer,\n33\t   when actually the same buffer is used for the FAPL and the VFD.\n34\t   This is implemented by using callbacks that simulate the standard\n35\t   functions for memory management (additional callbacks are used for\n36\t   the management of associated data structures). From the application\n37\t   standpoint, a file handle can be obtained from a file image by using\n38\t   the API routine H5LTopen_file_image(). This function takes a flag\n39\t   argument that indicates the HDF5 library how to handle the given image;\n40\t   several flag values can be combined by using the bitwise OR operator.\n41\t   Valid flag values include:\n42\t\n43\t   H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_OPEN_RW indicates the HDF5 library to open the file\n44\t   image in read/write mode. Default is read-only mode.\n45\t\n46\t   H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_DONT_COPY indicates the HDF5 library to not copy the\n47\t   supplied user buffer; the same buffer will be handled by the FAPL and\n48\t   the VFD driver. Default operation copies the user buffer to the FAPL and\n49\t   VFD driver.\n50\t\n51\t   H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_DONT_RELEASE indicates the HDF5 library to not release\n52\t   the buffer handled by the FAPL and the VFD upon closing. This flag value\n53\t   is only applicable when the flag value H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_DONT_COPY is set as\n54\t   well. The application is responsible to release the image buffer.\n55\t*/\n56\t\n57\t/* Data structure to pass application data to callbacks. */\n58\ttypedef struct {\n59\t    void    *app_image_ptr;   /* Pointer to application buffer */\n60\t    size_t   app_image_size;  /* Size of application buffer */\n61\t    void    *fapl_image_ptr;  /* Pointer to FAPL buffer */\n62\t    size_t   fapl_image_size; /* Size of FAPL buffer */\n63\t    int      fapl_ref_count;  /* Reference counter for FAPL buffer */\n64\t    void    *vfd_image_ptr;   /* Pointer to VFD buffer */\n65\t    size_t   vfd_image_size;  /* Size of VFD buffer */\n66\t    int      vfd_ref_count;   /* Reference counter for VFD buffer */\n67\t    unsigned flags;           /* Flags indicate how the file image will */\n68\t                              /* be open */\n69\t    int ref_count;            /* Reference counter on udata struct */\n70\t} H5LT_file_image_ud_t;\n71\t\n72\t/* callbacks prototypes for file image ops */\n73\tstatic void  *image_malloc(size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *udata);\n74\tstatic void  *image_memcpy(void *dest, const void *src, size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op,\n75\t                           void *udata);\n76\tstatic void  *image_realloc(void *ptr, size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *udata);\n77\tstatic herr_t image_free(void *ptr, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *udata);\n78\tstatic void  *udata_copy(void *udata);\n79\tstatic herr_t udata_free(void *udata);\n80\t\n81\t/* Definition of callbacks for file image operations. */\n82\t\n83\t/*-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n84\t * Function: image_malloc\n85\t *\n86\t * Purpose: Simulates malloc() function to avoid copying file images.\n87\t *          The application buffer is set to the buffer on only one FAPL.\n88\t *          Then the FAPL buffer can be copied to other FAPL buffers or\n89\t *          to only one VFD buffer.\n90\t *\n91\t * Return: Address of \"allocated\" buffer, if successful. Otherwise, it returns\n92\t *         NULL.\n93\t *\n94\t *-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n95\t */\n96\tstatic void *\n97\timage_malloc(size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *_udata)\n98\t{\n99\t    H5LT_file_image_ud_t *udata        = (H5LT_file_image_ud_t *)_udata;\n100\t    void                 *return_value = NULL;"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"78b03bfe-9de1-460b-8747-2e452ecc1588","uuid":"bd9fbe1c-64c4-4275-9904-7fbe5158c978","timestamp":"2026-06-06T19:37:26.568Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/work/agent/target-src/hl/src/H5LT.c","content":"/* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *\n * Copyright by The HDF Group.                                               *\n * All rights reserved.                                                      *\n *                                                                           *\n * This file is part of HDF5.  The full HDF5 copyright notice, including     *\n * terms governing use, modification, and redistribution, is contained in    *\n * the LICENSE file, which can be found at the root of the source code       *\n * distribution tree, or in https://www.hdfgroup.org/licenses.               *\n * If you do not have access to either file, you may request a copy from     *\n * help@hdfgroup.org.                                                        *\n * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * */\n\n#include \"H5LTprivate.h\"\n\n/* For Lex and Yacc */\n#define COL       3\n#define LIMIT     512\n#define INCREMENT 1024\n#define TMP_LEN   256\n#define MAX(a, b) (((a) > (b)) ? (a) : (b))\nsize_t input_len;\nchar  *myinput;\nsize_t indent = 0;\n\n/* File Image operations\n\n   A file image is a representation of an HDF5 file in a memory\n   buffer. In order to perform operations on an image in a similar way\n   to a  file, the application buffer is copied to a FAPL buffer, which\n   in turn is copied to a VFD buffer. Buffer copying can decrease\n   performance, especially when using large file images. A solution to\n   this issue is to simulate the copying of the application buffer,\n   when actually the same buffer is used for the FAPL and the VFD.\n   This is implemented by using callbacks that simulate the standard\n   functions for memory management (additional callbacks are used for\n   the management of associated data structures). From the application\n   standpoint, a file handle can be obtained from a file image by using\n   the API routine H5LTopen_file_image(). This function takes a flag\n   argument that indicates the HDF5 library how to handle the given image;\n   several flag values can be combined by using the bitwise OR operator.\n   Valid flag values include:\n\n   H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_OPEN_RW indicates the HDF5 library to open the file\n   image in read/write mode. Default is read-only mode.\n\n   H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_DONT_COPY indicates the HDF5 library to not copy the\n   supplied user buffer; the same buffer will be handled by the FAPL and\n   the VFD driver. Default operation copies the user buffer to the FAPL and\n   VFD driver.\n\n   H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_DONT_RELEASE indicates the HDF5 library to not release\n   the buffer handled by the FAPL and the VFD upon closing. This flag value\n   is only applicable when the flag value H5LT_FILE_IMAGE_DONT_COPY is set as\n   well. The application is responsible to release the image buffer.\n*/\n\n/* Data structure to pass application data to callbacks. */\ntypedef struct {\n    void    *app_image_ptr;   /* Pointer to application buffer */\n    size_t   app_image_size;  /* Size of application buffer */\n    void    *fapl_image_ptr;  /* Pointer to FAPL buffer */\n    size_t   fapl_image_size; /* Size of FAPL buffer */\n    int      fapl_ref_count;  /* Reference counter for FAPL buffer */\n    void    *vfd_image_ptr;   /* Pointer to VFD buffer */\n    size_t   vfd_image_size;  /* Size of VFD buffer */\n    int      vfd_ref_count;   /* Reference counter for VFD buffer */\n    unsigned flags;           /* Flags indicate how the file image will */\n                              /* be open */\n    int ref_count;            /* Reference counter on udata struct */\n} H5LT_file_image_ud_t;\n\n/* callbacks prototypes for file image ops */\nstatic void  *image_malloc(size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *udata);\nstatic void  *image_memcpy(void *dest, const void *src, size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op,\n                           void *udata);\nstatic void  *image_realloc(void *ptr, size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *udata);\nstatic herr_t image_free(void *ptr, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *udata);\nstatic void  *udata_copy(void *udata);\nstatic herr_t udata_free(void *udata);\n\n/* Definition of callbacks for file image operations. */\n\n/*-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n * Function: image_malloc\n *\n * Purpose: Simulates malloc() function to avoid copying file images.\n *          The application buffer is set to the buffer on only one FAPL.\n *          Then the FAPL buffer can be copied to other FAPL buffers or\n *          to only one VFD buffer.\n *\n * Return: Address of \"allocated\" buffer, if successful. Otherwise, it returns\n *         NULL.\n *\n *-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n */\nstatic void *\nimage_malloc(size_t size, H5FD_file_image_op_t file_image_op, void *_udata)\n{\n    H5LT_file_image_ud_t *udata        = (H5LT_file_image_ud_t *)_udata;\n    void                 *return_value = NULL;","numLines":100,"startLine":1,"totalLines":3520}}}
